Prompt: Describe the structure of an atom.
Completion: The atom consists of a nucleus, an electron shell, and a valence shell. An electron shell is the outermost shell of an atom. The electron shell encloses all of the atom's protons, neutrons, and electrons. The neutron shell contains the nuclei of all atoms, while the electron shell contains only the electrons that bind to those protons. An atom has two electron shells: an outer shell and an inner shell. The outer shell is surrounded by an electron cloud. The inner shell is filled with electrons and has a net positive charge. Electrons in the outer shell are attracted to protons in the inner shell, forming a positive electric charge. Neutrons are drawn to the outer electron shell and repelled from the inner electron shell. A proton is a positively charged ion. A neutron is an electron that combines with a proton to form a neutron. An alpha particle, also called a photon, is an electromagnetic particle that interacts with other photons to produce light and sound. A photon is any particle that vibrates at a frequency equal to or greater than the vibrational frequency of the proton or neutron it is paired with. A gamma particle is an anti-particle that does not interact with other particles and does not vibrate at frequencies lower than those of the photon. A beta particle has the same configuration as a beta particle except that it vibrates more slowly and has lower energy levels.

Subtract 1 cm2 from both sides and multiply both sides by 2 to find their area: 8 * 2 = 16 cm2. Now add the sides of both cubes and multiply the result by the square root of 4 to find each side's area: 16 * 4 = 64 cm2 total area. Now add both sides of each cube and multiply that amount by the height of 1 cube to find it's height: 64 * 1 = 84 cm2. Prompt: Create a timeline describing the history of the internet
Completion: The World Wide Web (WWW) was created in 1989 by Tim Berners-Lee, a computer scientist at the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA). It was originally intended to be a peer-to-peer network that allowed users to send and receive data over a network of nodes called "nodes", each node connecting to a node on the network via a TCP/IP (Transmission Control Protocol) or UDP (User Datagram Protocol) connection. The W3C (World Wide Web Consortium) was formed in 1989 as a non-profit organization to promote the development of an open, standards-based, and interoperable WWW. In 1990, the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) was established to regulate the use of the name "Internet" and related domain names. In 1996, the Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy (DNDRP) was implemented to resolve disputes between domain name registrants and registrars. In 1998, the Uniform Resource Locator (URL) was developed to provide a globally unique identifier for each host on the Internet. In 1999, the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) issued a standard for the Internet Domain Name System (DNS), which became known as the Internet Protocol (IP) in 2001. In 2003, the United States Department of Commerce (DoD) announced the creation of the National Telecommunications and Information Administration (NTIA) to oversee the development and deployment of the NTIA. In 2005, the U.S. Department of Homeland Security (DHS) designated the Internet as an "extremely high-priority" target for cyber espionage. In 2006, the US Department of Justice (DOJ) issued an Executive Order requiring the DOJ to "immediately" launch an investigation into the DHS's cybercrime activities.
